fields.test_description: Polycystic ovary disease or syndrome is a profile that assesses the functions and levels of various hormones . Complications and abnormalities in androgens,estrogens and gonadotropins cause this syndrome.

This assays detecting unbound or free form of thyroid hormones are highly sensitive to detect thyroid dysfunction such as, hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism. It includes 3 tests: free t3 (triiodothyronine), free t4 (thyroxine) and ultrasensitive tsh (thyroid stimulating hormone). Free Triiodothyronine [FT3]. The amount of the T3 hormone in blood indicates over or underactivity of the thyroid gland. High T3 levels may indicate over-function of thyroid gland while reduced levels may be indicative of underactivity of thyroid, known as hypothyroidism. Free Thyroxine (FT4) . Thyroxine is the hormone secreted by your thyroid gland. T4 levels in blood are used to determine over or underactivity of the thyroid gland. The most common cause of thyroid dysfunction is autoimmune disease. Graves disease causes hyperthyroidism (overactivity) and Hashimoto thyroiditis causes hypothyroidism (underactivity).

Creatinine is a waste product and is cleared from the blood entirely by the kidney. Decreased clearance by the kidney results in increased blood creatinine.  The amount of creatinine produced per day depends on muscle bulk. Thus there is a difference in creatinine ranges between males and females, with lower creatinine values in children and those with increased muscle bulk.  Diet and exercise also influences creatinine value. Creatinine can change as much as 30% after ingestion of red meat and exercise. Creatinine values are used as an indicator of the functioning of your kidney.

AST (Aspartate Aminotransferase) also known as SGOT is an enzyme found in the liver that helps convert proteins into energy for liver cells. When the liver is damaged, SGOT is released into the bloodstream and the levels might increase.  Mild elevations may sometimes be of no significance.

ALT (Alanine Aminotransferase) also known as SGPT is an enzyme that helps to metabolise amino acids.  Like ALT, AST is normally present in blood at low levels. An increase in AST may indicate liver damage, disease or muscle damage. Mild elevations may sometimes be of no significance.
GGT is an enzyme in the blood. Higher than normal levels may indicate liver and bile duct damage. This is often raised in persons with fatty liver or even in case of dietary indiscretion.

Sodium is an electrolyte that is vital to nerve and muscle and brain function and helps regulate the amount of fluid in the body. Potassium is an electrolyte that plays an important role to control your body’s fluid levels, acid-base balance, and nerve and muscle activity. Potassium is an essential nutrient that you consume in your daily diet. Potassium rich foods include bananas, citrus fruits and certain green vegetables. In certain conditions, abnormal levels may be used to assess the functioning of vital organs such as heart and kidney.

As the name suggests TSH is a hormone that stimulates the thyroid gland to secrete hormones. Thyroid gland is a butterfly shaped gland present in the middle part of the neck, and produces hormones that control various body functions.   Levels of TSH in blood may indicate under- and over-activity of the thyroid gland. However, the TSH levels may vary in a normal individual.  TSH levels follow the body clock (diurnal variations), with a difference of approximately +/- 50% between the peak and the low values. Hence it is always advisable to get subsequent TSH (ultrasensitive) tests done at similar times to obtain comparative values.   Thyroid levels may be deranged in serious non-thyroid illness such as trauma, infection, cancer, metabolic diseases and psychiatric disorders. Thyroid levels are affected during pregnancy and menstruation.. TSH levels may be deranged in various cases of thyroiditis or inflammation of thyroid gland.
